      <p>Scanners and mobile phone cameras rely on internal hardware gyroscopes to guess the orientation of a page. If the paper was fed slightly angled into an automatic document feeder (ADF) tray, or if you held your phone completely flat over a desk while taking a picture, the software often gets confused. It saves the image with the wrong EXIF metadata. When you convert those raw images into a PDF, that incorrect, sideways orientation gets hard-locked into the file's code.</p>

